{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is cross-module handoff: three source clients -> aggregation/orchestration -> summary input payload. A unit test of one formatter function is too low because the behavior text requires inclusion of data from all three upstream modules. System was considered and rejected because the behavior does not require real network/OS effects; in-process fakes for the three source adapters are sufficient to catch missing-source wiring bugs. Agentic was considered and rejected because this behavior checks input assembly, not model output quality.","test_description":"Wire real orchestrator + source adapter interfaces with controlled fakes for metrics/issues/deploy logs, execute one report build, and assert the exact payload sent to summary-generation contains fields from all three sources (and correct source-to-field mapping).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is resilience behavior at module boundaries: source failure handling + section rendering + pipeline continuation. Unit is too low because the failure appears when error state propagates across components. System was considered and rejected because a deterministic in-process failure from one source adapter (timeout/exception) reproduces the required failure mode without real network. Agentic was considered and rejected because correctness here is fallback control-flow (`rather than aborting`), not LLM judgment quality.","test_description":"Run report generation with two source adapters returning valid data and one adapter failing; assert process completes, output includes a `data unavailable` marker in the failed section, and remaining sections are present.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on semantic quality of generated narrative vs input facts (representation accuracy), which a stubbed model would hide. Per behavior text (`accurately represents`), the failure boundary is model decision/output quality, not just wrapper plumbing. Workflow was considered and rejected because only one agentic decision point is required (summary generation), not multiple agentic stages in sequence.","test_description":"Use real summary model calls on representative weekly datasets; score outputs against factuality checks (key metric/value presence, no contradictions/hallucinated values), with repeated runs to detect nondeterministic misses and threshold-based pass criteria.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly targets end-to-end delivery to a real inbox, crossing real I/O boundaries (source APIs + email transport). Mocking can hide real failures in auth, transport, envelope formatting, or provider acceptance. Agentic was considered and rejected because this behavior’s assertion is delivery outcome (`reaches ... inbox correctly`), not summary-quality judgment. Workflow was considered and rejected because no multi-agentic sequence is specified.","test_description":"Execute the scheduled report pipeline in an environment using reachable test instances of the three data sources and a real mail test inbox/service; verify one run produces an email received by configured recipients with expected subject/body/attachments and no dropped sections.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure mode includes real external-service unreachability plus persistence/retry across runs. A mock mail client can miss real transport error shapes and retry-trigger conditions; behavior text explicitly centers on unreachable service and next-run recovery. Integration was considered but rejected because the boundary under test is app<->real email service failure semantics. Agentic and Workflow were considered and rejected because no model-output-quality requirement or multi-agentic chain is stated.","test_description":"Run pipeline with email endpoint intentionally unreachable (e.g., blocked/invalid SMTP host) and confirm report is persisted locally; run next scheduled execution with email service restored and verify persisted report is retried and successfully delivered, then fallback artifact state is updated/cleared as designed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
